00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:12.400
are the definitions of addition, multiplication,&nbsp;
and so on? And how does one actually prove the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:17.400
laws of arithmetic for these objects? That&nbsp;
is what we're interested in here today.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:23.440
So, our first approach to possibly setting up&nbsp;
Hindu-Arabic numbers is to regard them as short&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:32.880
forms for primitive natural numbers—that they&nbsp;
provide us with a convenient way of concisely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:41.040
expressing these primitive natural numbers, which&nbsp;
can be quite onerous to write down and express. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:46.240
what we do is we look at the primitive natural&nbsp;
numbers, and we give them the usual names. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:54.360
this one here is called zero, and we give it&nbsp;
the alternate symbol that we're familiar with.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.360 --> 00:06:00.800
This thing here with a single mark in it is the&nbsp;
number one with its usual number. This is two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.800 --> 00:06:07.480
this is three, and so on. This thing here&nbsp;
would be twenty-seven written like this. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:12.440
we're all very familiar with the system here, but&nbsp;
we know that it does take some explaining. I mean,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:16.320
to actually explain it to someone&nbsp;
who didn't know what it was about,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:24.040
we'd have to talk about how we take one of these&nbsp;
big M-sets of marks and subdivide them into ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:28.400
tens, hundreds, thousands, and so&nbsp;
on, and then count the numbers of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:35.440
those various things and then string them&nbsp;
together in our sort of Hindu-Arabic list.

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:41.960
So if we proceed this way—and this is a&nbsp;
valid, possible way of proceeding—okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:47.360
that a Hindu-Arabic number is just a&nbsp;
short form for a primitive natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:52.640
then the definition of operations on&nbsp;
Hindu-Arabic numbers simply reduces to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:58.720
those of the primitive natural numbers. It's&nbsp;
just a reflection of this prior arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:04.720
that we already have in place for the&nbsp;
primitive natural numbers. So instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:17.960
of saying "1111 + 1111 = 1111," something like&nbsp;
that, we might rather say "9 + 13 = 22." Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:29.520
it's just a shorthand for it. So logically, then,&nbsp;
nothing really too much in addition is required.

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:36.640
So if we do take this approach, then Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
arithmetic is completely equivalent logically to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:40.920
the arithmetic with natural numbers that we&nbsp;
already have—the arithmetic with primitive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:50.000
natural numbers. And we can flag this usage in&nbsp;
the following way. So let's write the following:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:58.680
that if we write seven is of type "nat," okay,&nbsp;
what that means is that seven is defined as this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:05.680
thing here. So this is the actual object in&nbsp;
"nat." And when we write this, we agree that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:15.320
this thing here is defined to be this. In&nbsp;
other words, this is another name for this.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:21.800
Okay, why don't we do this then? End of story?&nbsp;
Because there's a serious disadvantage with this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:28.080
but it's a logical disadvantage that really only&nbsp;
becomes apparent once we step outside the bounds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:34.640
of familiar, relatively small arithmetic.&nbsp;
The disadvantage is that we are logically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:41.960
restricted to numbers less than 10^200.&nbsp;
Why? Because this is the maximum possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:48.800
size of a primitive natural number in our&nbsp;
universe, roughly. We've seen that if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:56.120
want to write down a bunch of ones or marks,&nbsp;
okay, the very, very most that you could do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.120 --> 00:09:01.520
that is determined by how much room there is&nbsp;
in the universe and how small you can write.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:05.720
And if you're writing at the very smallest&nbsp;
scale, which is, let's say, the Planck scale,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:14.440
and you're writing to fill the entire universe,&nbsp;
then we've decided that there's roughly 10^200&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:22.080
such little Planck cubes filling our universe,&nbsp;
very roughly. Okay, and that's then an upper&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:28.640
bound for the number of marks that you can make.&nbsp;
Of course, you could never make anywhere near that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:34.880
many marks, but at least in principle, we can&nbsp;
contemplate something like up to that amount.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:42.640
Okay, but we are constrained roughly somewhere at&nbsp;
this level, right? We are not able to conceptually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:53.000
even imagine in our universe M-sets of stuff&nbsp;
with a lot more than this number. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:59.920
these various numbers that we've been&nbsp;
talking about—Z or Z-prime or 3-star&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:07.440
n^2 4—right? These numbers are so big that&nbsp;
they completely overwhelm the possibility&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:16.280
of actually exhibiting an M-set with&nbsp;
this number of objects in it. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:23.040
so that means that if we're going to attach our&nbsp;
Hindu-Arabic numbers to primitive natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:28.200
then we are constrained by whatever bounds we&nbsp;
have on the primitive natural numbers, and we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:35.760
constrained because the universe is probably only&nbsp;
so big, and we can write probably only so small.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:42.440
So let me illustrate this point by giving you&nbsp;
an example of something that's arithmetically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:48.440
impossible for us, even though we would actually&nbsp;
want it to be possible. So consider the question&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:57.120
of adding this natural number to one. Well, this&nbsp;
is the natural number 96511. I'm not going to tell&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.120 --> 00:11:02.440
you all of it, okay? You can read it there.&nbsp;
It's a natural number with roughly about 200&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:11.440
digits. Therefore, this natural number is so&nbsp;
big that it represents the size of a set which,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:19.240
or a multiset which, is impossible to conceive of&nbsp;
in our universe. We cannot write down and exhibit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.240 --> 00:11:26.840
even theoretically, even in principle, an&nbsp;
M-set or a set which has this number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.840 --> 00:11:32.760
objects in it. So if we're thinking about this&nbsp;
as representing a primitive natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:39.520
we are just stepping beyond the bounds of what&nbsp;
we actually can do. So we would have to look at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:44.000
something like this and say, "I'm sorry, this does&nbsp;
not make any sense because we cannot interpret&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:52.240
this thing as a primitive natural number." But&nbsp;
this is too limiting for us. This is too limiting.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:57.960
We want to be able to make calculations like&nbsp;
this because we all could make this calculation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.960 --> 00:12:03.880
right? The end of doing this is you just&nbsp;
change that three to a four. Our computers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:09.960
can deal with numbers which are this big—they&nbsp;
can do all kinds of great computations with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:17.360
them. And if we're doing geometry in a sort of&nbsp;
integer framework or rational number framework,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:17.360 --> 00:12:25.640
once you go a few steps in complexity in some&nbsp;
actual specific situation where you're actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:30.080
making computations, then you shouldn't&nbsp;
be surprised to have bigger and bigger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:36.320
numerators and denominators occurring—that'll&nbsp;
typically be what happens, okay? When you make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:41.040
the addition of fractions or multiplication&nbsp;
of fractions, then the denominators and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:48.200
numerators generally get bigger. So every time you&nbsp;
make a computation, then you're increasing sizes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:53.720
and so it doesn't take that long before, you know,&nbsp;
we can realistically end up with numerators and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:59.280
denominators that are of this order. We want to&nbsp;
be able to deal with them—we don't want to just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:08.040
throw up our hands and say, "I'm sorry, that's no&nbsp;
longer supported by our theoretical constructs."

00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:14.480
So we want to do bigger arithmetic, and&nbsp;
so we need to free "num" from "nat."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:18.440
We do not want to identify these&nbsp;
two things. We do not want "num"&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:25.800
to just be a replacement or a short&nbsp;
form for "nat." That's too limiting.

00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:33.360
All right, so notice how this understanding&nbsp;
really does depend on our investigations of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:38.600
bigger numbers and our investigation about&nbsp;
complexity, right? We've been thinking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:42.920
complexity—we have this sense that, you&nbsp;
know, there are limits out there in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.920 --> 00:13:49.040
of how big you can write down expressions&nbsp;
and correspondingly how big are the numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.040 --> 00:13:54.840
that you have some realistic hope of writing&nbsp;
down in some fashion or another. All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:59.040
so we're trying to address that—we're not&nbsp;
pretending that we're living in some unearthly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:05.160
kind of universe where there's an infinite amount&nbsp;
of room and we can just do infinitely many things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:14.440
just by waving our hands around. We're not doing&nbsp;
that—we want to really pin things down solidly.

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:18.080
All right, so what we want to do is we&nbsp;
want to free "num" from "nat." We want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:24.320
to have our Hindu-Arabic number system&nbsp;
allow us bigger arithmetic than we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:30.640
do just with "nat." Not as great, but&nbsp;
we want to do something more. All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:36.440
so let's look at a separate line of inquiry. Let's&nbsp;
think about Hindu-Arabic numbers as a separate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:43.040
system from "nat," but which correlates with it.&nbsp;
So that's our aim—to try to see some direction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:51.080
in which we could create a theory of natural&nbsp;
numbers based on Hindu-Arabic representation.

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:57.200
Okay, so this is a lot more work. This is a&nbsp;
lot fancier than dealing with primitive natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.200 --> 00:15:05.520
numbers. It's several orders of magnitude more&nbsp;
complicated, in fact. In fact, I claim it has not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:12.560
yet been done in 2016. There's no place where&nbsp;
you can find a proper theory of Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:20.400
numbers. In particular, Peano-type axioms—some&nbsp;
of you will have heard of an axiomatic approach&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:28.560
to numbers—so Peano axioms don't really help us&nbsp;
either because Peano is resting on the idea of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:35.640
building up natural numbers by successors. And if&nbsp;
you want to start with one and then you add one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:38.720
and then you add one, and then you add one,&nbsp;
and so on, and you want to kind of build up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.720 --> 00:15:45.680
an arithmetic, you're really essentially in&nbsp;
the realm of primitive natural numbers. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:52.400
so Peano is just an axiomatic approach to what&nbsp;
we're calling natural numbers. In fact, it doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:59.360
really aid us considerably, but we'll talk about&nbsp;
Peano at some other point. But in any case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:05.800
Peano is not going to help us go beyond the&nbsp;
primitive natural numbers. We need to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:11.400
something else—we need to go beyond this&nbsp;
need to have our numbers connected with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:18.280
an actual M-set or a sequence of things&nbsp;
that we can write down starting from one.

00:16:18.280 --> 00:16:23.400
Okay, so here's a rough outline of&nbsp;
how to proceed. So here's a program&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:29.120
that somebody could think very carefully&nbsp;
about and work towards creating a theory&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:37.080
of Hindu-Arabic numbers. Isn't it remarkable&nbsp;
that in 2016, such a program is possible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:45.400
that there's this road that could be gone down&nbsp;
by somebody who's careful and serious enough&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:51.240
and really wants to do some work to establish&nbsp;
arithmetic? That's what we're talking about.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.240 --> 00:16:56.760
It's not some tangential thing built on top&nbsp;
of the extremities of a theory built on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:05.200
extremities of some other theory. This is core&nbsp;
mathematics we're discussing here, isn't it?

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:09.520
Okay, so how could we start? We could&nbsp;
start by defining Hindu-Arabic numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:15.560
as expressions like this. Okay, that's not&nbsp;
so hard to do. So a Hindu-Arabic number is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:19.840
an expression like this. And what does that&nbsp;
mean? Well, it's a list, or if you like,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.840 --> 00:17:28.600
a string of digits. The digits are all&nbsp;
taken from this set, the usual ones:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:35.800
0 to 9. And the strings have the property that,&nbsp;
well, they can be arbitrary, except for the rule&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:42.320
that they can't begin with zero—they can't&nbsp;
begin with zero except for the single number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:48.280
zero itself. That's the only number that can&nbsp;
start with the digit zero. By "start," I mean&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:57.600
the leftmost digit is zero, and all lists must&nbsp;
be non-empty. We're not allowing any empty lists.

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:05.120
All right, so that is a reasonable&nbsp;
definition of what a Hindu-Arabic number is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.120 --> 00:18:11.160
and we can agree that you have a Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
number precisely when you can write down such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.160 --> 00:18:18.960
a string. You can write down a string like&nbsp;
this one—you have a Hindu-Arabic number. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:25.880
we don't need to suppose that there's some&nbsp;
set somewhere that this is counting. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:32.080
the Hindu-Arabic number is just this string&nbsp;
that you write down. That is a very sensible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:41.080
and concrete and reasonable way of defining these&nbsp;
things into existence. That'd be like step one.

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:46.440
Okay, so now that we have the objects, the&nbsp;
numbers themselves, we are obliged to define&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:53.960
the operations—so say addition and multiplication,&nbsp;
the two ones that we usually start with. How are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.960 --> 00:19:01.560
we going to define these? So note that now it's no&nbsp;
longer possible for us to go back to the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:09.200
numbers. We can't say, "Take your Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
number and find an M-set or a collection or a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:16.240
set that has that many objects in it, and take&nbsp;
your other Hindu-Arabic number and find another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:22.840
M-set that has that many, and then dump them&nbsp;
together, and then count how many we have." Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:28.720
that works only if we're in the realm of&nbsp;
possibilities for exhibiting these M-sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:29.480 --> 00:19:37.120
and we've already sort of flagged that we are&nbsp;
going beyond that. Okay, so we cannot rely on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:42.240
just converting our Hindu-Arabic numbers&nbsp;
to natural numbers and working there. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.240 --> 00:19:47.560
nevertheless, we can still connect with&nbsp;
what we're doing with natural numbers.

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:54.680
So we could create addition and multiplication&nbsp;
tables. Okay, and so here's an addition table&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:54.680 --> 00:20:00.200
for just the digits themselves, and here is a&nbsp;
multiplication table for the digits themselves.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:04.520
Well, the tables are not complete, but I'm sure&nbsp;
you can all complete them. Okay, so one could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:10.600
sort of write down these tables and say, "This&nbsp;
is how we're going to define the addition of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:10.600 --> 00:20:17.080
just our Hindu-Arabic numbers, which are given by&nbsp;
single digits. If we want to know what is 2 + 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:21.640
we look under the table and we say, 'Ah, it's&nbsp;
8.' If we want to know what is 2 * 7, we look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:21.640 --> 00:20:31.400
under the table and we say, 'Ah, it's 14.'" Okay,&nbsp;
so of course this table doesn't tell us how to add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:40.880
more generally, but it's a start. Okay, so we give&nbsp;
these tables, and we define the operations on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:47.720
single digits this way. And of course, we all know&nbsp;
that these things do come from our understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:53.480
of natural numbers, the primitive natural numbers,&nbsp;
and how addition and multiplication work for them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.480 --> 00:20:59.000
But in fact, we don't really need to say so. Okay,&nbsp;
we can just say, "Here are two tables, and we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:06.880
going to define addition and multiplication by&nbsp;
these tables." That's how we tell our computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:12.920
how to add digits—we don't have to explain to&nbsp;
the computer where we got these things from.

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:17.720
All right, so now for the second part of that&nbsp;
second step—we need to extend our understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:17.720 --> 00:21:25.040
or definition of addition and multiplication&nbsp;
to general Hindu-Arabic numbers. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:25.040 --> 00:21:31.120
because we've had lots of experience at this in&nbsp;
primary school, we know at least in principle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:37.720
how this should proceed—or roughly, anyway.&nbsp;
Because we know how to use those addition and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:45.400
multiplication tables to add and multiply more&nbsp;
general numbers. If we want to add 237 and 49,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:51.040
we know that we start on the right and we&nbsp;
add seven and nine using the table—we get 16,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:55.800
we write the six, we put the one up there,&nbsp;
and then we add three and four, we get seven,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:55.800 --> 00:22:03.680
we add the one, we get eight, and then we bring&nbsp;
this two down. If we want to multiply 237 by 49,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:11.200
well, we multiply 9 * 7—63, we write the three,&nbsp;
we put the six up there; then 9 * 3 is 27,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:17.920
we add the 6—that's 33, we put a three down,&nbsp;
there's a three coming up there, etc. All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:25.080
so it's a question then of taking the familiar&nbsp;
knowledge about how to actually add Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:25.080 --> 00:22:30.720
numbers and telling our computer how to do&nbsp;
that—that's essentially what the definition is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.720 --> 00:22:42.080
So extending our definition from single-digit&nbsp;
operations to general string operations.

00:22:42.080 --> 00:22:47.360
All right, so this is a fair amount of work,&nbsp;
but it's not impossible. You could certainly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:53.560
program a computer to do this, and in fact, if&nbsp;
you look at computers that do have code that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.560 --> 00:23:02.360
works on Hindu-Arabic numbers, well, they have&nbsp;
something like this, right? That's what they do.

00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:08.760
And then we have a third challenge, which is&nbsp;
to prove the laws of arithmetic. This is more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:13.240
challenging than you might think because you&nbsp;
are not allowed to use the prior knowledge of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:19.800
arithmetic with natural numbers, with primitive&nbsp;
natural numbers, okay, except for small numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:19.800 --> 00:23:28.120
So we can use the fact that for small numbers&nbsp;
we know that 3 + 7 + 8 is the same as 3 + 7 + 8,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:28.120 --> 00:23:34.600
you know, so we can use those things. But&nbsp;
we don't know that associativity or, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:40.520
the distributive law or even commutativity&nbsp;
is necessarily going to be operating on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:51.040
these huge Hindu-Arabic numbers. Of course,&nbsp;
we have this intuition that they will, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:57.800
but it's not a valid argument to say, "Well,&nbsp;
we just convert these big Hindu-Arabic numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:03.000
to M-sets, and then we do the primitive natural&nbsp;
number operations there; we know that things are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:10.240
commutative or associative or distributive there,&nbsp;
and then we go back up." That argument only holds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:17.040
up to the limits of our natural or primitive&nbsp;
natural number system, and we're proposing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:26.720
to go much beyond that. So we need separate,&nbsp;
independent proofs of the laws of arithmetic.

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:30.720
Can you appreciate that there's something to&nbsp;
be done here? And it's actually a considerable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:35.280
amount of work, and it's not at all,&nbsp;
you know, immediately obvious what the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:40.320
most efficient and elegant way of doing this&nbsp;
is. This would be a great Master's project,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:40.320 --> 00:24:44.720
I think, right? A student could easily&nbsp;
spend a year or two thinking about how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:52.640
to do this really in a nice, elegant&nbsp;
way—it would be very instructive.

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:58.600
Okay, and so if we went down this road, which&nbsp;
I'm broadly outlining here, we could put that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.600 --> 00:25:05.880
together and then get a new system, which we&nbsp;
could call "num"—Hindu-Arabic numbers—which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:15.800
extends the arithmetic of natural numbers&nbsp;
and coincides with it when there's overlap.

00:25:15.800 --> 00:25:20.800
So you've probably guessed that that's not&nbsp;
how we're going to proceed. We're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:20.800 --> 00:25:25.960
proceed down a different path. So this is&nbsp;
the third approach that I want to suggest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:33.240
to you in terms of establishing an arithmetic&nbsp;
for Hindu-Arabic numbers. So I propose that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:42.600
Hindu-Arabic numbers can be viewed as multisets,&nbsp;
and when we take this M-set point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:42.600 --> 00:25:52.200
then we can exploit things that we already&nbsp;
know, and we can create an alternate form of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:52.200 --> 00:25:58.920
Hindu-Arabic arithmetic. But it will require us to&nbsp;
think a little bit differently, so we have to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:06.720
prepared to shift our orientation a little bit—but&nbsp;
you're used to that anyway on this channel, right?

00:26:06.720 --> 00:26:10.400
Okay, so the motivation for this is&nbsp;
the following: suppose that we take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:10.400 --> 00:26:18.720
a Hindu-Arabic number like 43, which of course&nbsp;
is 3 + 4 * 10^1. So in terms of powers of 10,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:25.600
which is naturally what's going on here, it's&nbsp;
3 * 10^0 plus 4 * 10^1. So here's another way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:33.360
of representing that information as an M-set.&nbsp;
So here's an M-set—it's got square brackets and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:41.760
no commas, and it's got repetitions. There&nbsp;
are three singletons here—singletons with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:49.240
zeros in them—and there are four singletons&nbsp;
with ones in them, right? So these are just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:53.920
like lists with one element, and there&nbsp;
are three zeros here to represent the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:53.920 --> 00:26:59.880
fact that there's 3 * 10^0 in this Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
number, and there are four singletons with ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:08.320
to represent the fact that we have 4 * 10^1 in&nbsp;
this number here. So this is maybe rather long,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:15.880
but it is a legitimate way of representing the&nbsp;
information contained in that Hindu-Arabic number.

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:18.680
Let's say we have a slightly&nbsp;
bigger one, like 512. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:18.680 --> 00:27:26.280
that's 2 * 10^0 + 1 * 10^1 + 5 * 10^2. And&nbsp;
then that information can be represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:36.760
in an M-set point of view by having two&nbsp;
singletons of zeros, one singleton of one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:43.560
and five singletons of twos. This is then&nbsp;
an M-set which essentially contains the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:50.440
information encoded in this Hindu-Arabic number,&nbsp;
and it does so in a way that actually corresponds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:50.440 --> 00:27:56.080
with what we're writing down. So you could look&nbsp;
at this and reasonably easily write down this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:56.080 --> 00:28:05.040
thing here without having to convert to a natural&nbsp;
number—so we're not going via "nat" here, okay?

00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:09.880
Now, if we stare at these things, we say, "Wait&nbsp;
a minute, we've seen this kind of thing before."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:15.720
These are just "vexels"—these are the kinds&nbsp;
of objects we were playing around with when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:15.720 --> 00:28:24.200
we were talking about maxel theory, our sort&nbsp;
of novel point of view towards matrices and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:24.200 --> 00:28:32.560
elementary linear algebra, right? Vexels were&nbsp;
some kind of M-set replacement for vectors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:39.120
and they're exactly like this—they're just&nbsp;
multisets of singletons, a singleton being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:45.680
a list with a single natural number&nbsp;
in it, where a natural number now is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:52.080
allowed to be zero as well. That's a little&nbsp;
bit of a difference from previously, okay?

00:28:52.080 --> 00:28:58.640
So the possibility is now to harness&nbsp;
our earlier discussion, our earlier&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:08.200
discussion of vexels and that framework, to&nbsp;
harness that as a scaffolding to build up a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:08.200 --> 00:29:18.080
theory of Hindu-Arabic numbers. So we need&nbsp;
an arithmetic with vexels, and pleasantly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:27.560
this then also draws in earlier discussions&nbsp;
about pols and what we called poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:34.800
So we're going to be unifying a whole bunch of&nbsp;
things here—algebra in terms of poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:40.600
linear algebra in terms of these vexels, and&nbsp;
fundamental arithmetic in terms of Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:50.120
numbers are all going to start being part&nbsp;
of the same intimately connected story.

00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:53.440
We'll start on that next time.&nbsp;
Hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:58.040
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:29:58.040 --> 00:29:59.040
[Music]

